{
  "doc_id": "23009",
  "text": "Glutathione S-transferase (GST) expression vector pGEX-4T-2 (Pharmacia Biotech) was used to create a fusion protein between GST and the 48 C-terminal amino acids of the human βPP protein (GST-C48, amino acids 590-695, of βPP 695 ). GST and GST-C48 were expressed in E.coli and purified using glutathione-agarose affinity chromatography as previously described [CITATION_1] . VP16 protein and VP16-clone 230 fusion protein were labeled with [CITATION_2] S-methionine during in vitro translation using the TNT T7-coupled transcription-translation reticulocyte lysate system (Promega). Equal amounts of 35 S-labeled VP16 or VP16-230 reticulocyte lysate were diluted into 200 µl of binding buffer (50 mM Tris, pH 7.5, 150 mM NaCl) and incubated for 2 h at 4_C with affinity purified GST or GST-C48 fusion protein bound to glutathione-agarose beads, or anti-VP16 rabbit polyclonal antibodies (Upstate Biotechnology Inc., Lake Placid, NY) bound to protein A-agarose beads. After the incubation period, protein-protein complexes were washed three times in binding buffer and the retained [CITATION_3] S labeled proteins were then boiled in SDS sample buffer and resolved on a 14% Tricine-SDSpolyacrylamide gel [CITATION_4] . The gel was stained with coomassie blue to assess the relative levels of GST and GST-C48 used in the precipitation step and then soaked in EN 3 HANCE™ (DuPont) for 30 min, dried, and subjected to X-ray autoradiography.",
